{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"# S1 — Optional Streamable-HTTP transport for rebar-mcp + transport hardening\n\n## Why\nAuthentication in MCP is an HTTP-transport concern; the spec says stdio servers must not\nauthenticate. rebar-mcp is stdio-only today (`src/rebar/mcp_server.py`, `build_server().run()` with\nno transport arg). Before any verifier can exist there must be an HTTP transport to authenticate\nagainst. This story adds that transport and its network hardening — the foundation every auth story\nbuilds on — with stdio unchanged as the default. It also owns the SDK version pin, because it is\nthe first story to construct the SDK's HTTP transport / `TransportSecuritySettings`.\n\n## What\nAdd an **optional Streamable-HTTP transport** to rebar-mcp, selected by config, using the official\n`mcp` SDK's native support:\n- **Pin the SDK here:** set `mcp>=1.28.1,<2` in `pyproject.toml` (the v2-alpha renames the surface;\n  1.28.1 is at/above the DNS-rebinding fix GHSA-9h52-p55h-vw2f). All later stories build on this pin.\n- Extend the existing **flat** `McpConfig` dataclass and the flat `_SECTIONS['mcp']` key→coercer\n  dict in `src/rebar/_config_schema.py` (the one-level `coerce_sparse` architecture — NO nested\n  sub-tables) with flat scalar keys: `transport` (`stdio` default | `http`), `http_host` (default\n  `127.0.0.1`), `http_port` (default `8000`), `http_path` (default `/mcp`), `http_allowed_hosts`\n  (comma-separated), `http_allowed_origins` (comma-separated), and `allow_unauthenticated_http`\n  (bool, default `false`). Each is one dataclass field + one flat coercer entry, auto-deriving its\n  `REBAR_MCP_*` env var. This story registers these keys in `MCP_ENV_VARS` + `server.json` and\n  regenerates `docs/mcp-reference.md`/`docs/env-vars.md` for its slice (the CI drift gate\n  `scripts/check_server_manifest.py` must pass). NOTE: `scripts/gen_mcp_reference.py` currently\n  **hardcodes** the gate-env-var table (line ~208, the static tuple `(\"REBAR_MCP_READONLY\",\n  \"REBAR_MCP_ALLOW_LLM\", \"REBAR_MCP_ALLOW_JIRA_SYNC\")`) instead of iterating `MCP_ENV_VARS`; this\n  story changes it to iterate `MCP_ENV_VARS` so newly-added `REBAR_MCP_*` keys actually appear in the\n  regenerated reference (all later key-adding stories rely on this fix).\n- In `build_server`/`main`, when `transport=http` construct `FastMCP(\"rebar\", host=…, port=…,\n  transport_security=TransportSecuritySettings(...))` and run via `run(transport=\"streamable-http\")`;\n  the stdio path is unchanged.\n- **Explicit transport-security defaults:** DNS-rebinding/Origin protection **on**. For a loopback\n  bind, set explicit loopback allowlists (`127.0.0.1:<port>`, `localhost:<port>`, `[::1]:<port>` and\n  the matching `http://…` origins) rather than empty lists (empty + protection-on either 421s\n  localhost or degrades protection). Construct `host`/`port`/`transport_security` at `FastMCP(...)`\n  time, NOT via late attribute assignment (the documented \"421\" late-host bug).\n- **Non-loopback bind fail-closed gates:** a non-loopback `http_host` requires BOTH\n  `http_allowed_hosts` AND `http_allowed_origins` to be non-empty, AND an explicit TLS-at-edge\n  acknowledgment `REBAR_MCP_HTTP_TLS_AT_EDGE` (a flat `http_tls_at_edge` bool key) — because bearer\n  tokens and proxy secrets must never cross the network in cleartext; without it the server refuses\n  to start.\n- **Unauthenticated-HTTP guard:** `allow_unauthenticated_http` (env `REBAR_MCP_ALLOW_UNAUTHENTICATED_HTTP`)\n  read through the flat coercer (a resolved config field, NOT a bespoke `os.environ` read). Starting\n  `transport=http` with auth disabled refuses to start unless `allow_unauthenticated_http` is true.\n  (Auth config lands in S2; until then \"auth enabled\" is treated as false, so HTTP requires the ack.)\n\n## Approach & rationale\nUse the SDK's built-in Streamable-HTTP transport and `TransportSecuritySettings` rather than\nhand-rolling an ASGI server — the SDK provides both, keeping this a thin wiring change on a blessed\nseam, consistent with peer servers (GitHub/Grafana/Neon). Keep every config key flat to fit rebar's\nexisting `coerce_sparse` architecture (adding scalars alongside `readonly`/`allow_llm`/\n`allow_jira_sync`).\n\n## Scope\nThe transport + transport-security + the two fail-closed startup gates (non-loopback and\nunauthenticated-HTTP) + the SDK pin only. It ships **no** token verifiers and validates **no** token\n(that is S2+). A subset of the epic.\n\n## Security\nCrosses a trust boundary (opens a network listener). Mitigated here by: DNS-rebinding/Origin\nallowlisting on by default with explicit loopback defaults; loopback-only bind by default; a\nnon-loopback bind requiring both allowlists AND the explicit TLS-at-edge ack; and the fail-closed\nunauthenticated-HTTP refusal. TLS is terminated at an edge proxy (documented in S7); rebar binds\nHTTP behind it and never advertises or serves bearer auth in cleartext.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `pyproject.toml` pins `mcp>=1.28.1,<2`; `make typecheck` resolves the SDK imports used here.\n- [ ] `McpConfig` exposes the flat `transport`/`http_host`/`http_port`/`http_path`/\n      `http_allowed_hosts`/`http_allowed_origins`/`http_tls_at_edge`/`allow_unauthenticated_http`\n      keys as fields + `_SECTIONS['mcp']` coercer entries; unset → stdio, byte-identical to today\n      (observable: existing `tests/interfaces/facades/test_mcp.py` stdio suite passes).\n- [ ] Integration test (tier: integration — an in-process ASGI HTTP client, e.g. httpx\n      `ASGITransport`, driving the SDK's Streamable-HTTP ASGI entrypoint within its lifespan/session\n      context; concrete entrypoint resolved against the pinned `mcp>=1.28.1,<2` at implementation\n      time; a unit test cannot cross the Starlette transport/middleware seam) boots with\n      `transport=http` (and `allow_unauthenticated_http=true` set for this auth-off boot) and asserts\n      a baseline MCP request succeeds (observable oracle: HTTP 200 + valid `initialize` response).\n- [ ] Integration test asserts a disallowed `Host` → **421** and a disallowed `Origin` → **403**,\n      while an allowed loopback request passes (negative control in the same test), confirming the\n      explicit loopback defaults work with protection ON.\n- [ ] Unit/integration test asserts a non-loopback `http_host` refuses to start when either\n      allowlist is empty OR `http_tls_at_edge` is unset, and starts when both allowlists AND the ack\n      are supplied (observable oracle: process exits non-zero / raises a clear message vs boots).\n- [ ] Unit/integration test asserts `transport=http` with auth off and no\n      `REBAR_MCP_ALLOW_UNAUTHENTICATED_HTTP` refuses to start, and starts when the ack is set.\n- [ ] Integration test asserts session-id replay cannot hijack a principal: an `Mcp-Session-Id`\n      captured from one authenticated client, replayed by a DIFFERENT client that presents no valid\n      token of its own, is NEVER served in the first principal's authenticated context (single\n      observable oracle: the replayed request does not return the original principal's authorized\n      access — it is denied / treated as unauthenticated). If the pinned SDK is found not to bind\n      session→principal, this story adds the binding; the test asserts the property either way.\n- [ ] `MCP_ENV_VARS` + `server.json` include the new keys; `scripts/gen_mcp_reference.py` iterates\n      `MCP_ENV_VARS` (not a hardcoded tuple) so the regenerated `docs/mcp-reference.md`/\n      `docs/env-vars.md` include every new `REBAR_MCP_*` key; and `scripts/check_server_manifest.py`\n      passes (observable oracle: the regenerated reference contains the new key names and the drift\n      test is green).\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` pass.\n\n## Compatibility\nAdditive: stdio remains default; all new keys default to today's behavior when unset. The only\ncross-cutting change is the `mcp` pin, backward-compatible with existing installs. No change to the\nexisting 48 tools or the stdio path."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784070352647500001,"uuid":"e34758c6-85ab-407b-acbd-6c8d00dd5099"}